      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Early 20th-century eugenicists used flawed arguments to justify racial hierarchies, primarily citing the supposed superiority of \"white\" or \"Northern European\" populations. They claimed that certain racial groups, such as blacks and Jews, were inherently inferior due to their physical characteristics, intelligence, and cultural practices. They also relied on pseudo-scientific theories, like Social Darwinism, to argue that the strongest and most \"fit\" individuals should reproduce to preserve the \"races.\" These arguments were often rooted in a distorted view of science and a deep-seated prejudice against those deemed \"undesirable.\"",
